05173nam a22007455i 9780691190549DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911905497 a10.1515/97806911905492doi  a(DE-B1597)506366  a(OCoLC)1083671325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aNA1370 7aART0150902bisacsh04a724/.1609496182231 aRüstem, Ünver, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOttoman Baroque :bThe Architectural Refashioning of Eighteenth-Century Istanbul /cÜnver Rüstem. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Captions, Transliterations, and Translations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. SETTING THE SCENE -- tCHAPTER 2. PLEASING TIMES AND THEIR "PLEASING NEW STYLE" -- tCHAPTER 3. A TRADITION REBORN -- tCHAPTER 4. THE OLD, THE NEW, AND THE IN-BETWEEN -- tCHAPTER 5. AT THE SULTAN'S THRESHOLD -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tImage Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new approach to late Ottoman visual culture and its place in the worldWith its idiosyncratic yet unmistakable adaptation of European Baroque models, the eighteenth-century architecture of Istanbul has frequently been dismissed by modern observers as inauthentic and derivative, a view reflecting broader unease with notions of Western influence on Islamic cultures. In Ottoman Baroque-the first English-language book on the topic-Ünver Rüstem provides a compelling reassessment of this building style and shows how between 1740 and 1800 the Ottomans consciously co-opted European forms to craft a new, politically charged, and globally resonant image for their empire's capital.Rüstem reclaims the label "Ottoman Baroque" as a productive framework for exploring the connectedness of Istanbul's eighteenth-century buildings to other traditions of the period. Using a wealth of primary sources, he demonstrates that this architecture was in its own day lauded by Ottomans and foreigners alike for its fresh, cosmopolitan effect. Purposefully and creatively assimilated, the style's cross-cultural borrowings were combined with Byzantine references that asserted the Ottomans' entitlement to the Classical artistic heritage of Europe. Such aesthetic rebranding was part of a larger endeavor to reaffirm the empire's power at a time of intensified East-West contact, taking its boldest shape in a series of imperial mosques built across the city as landmarks of a state-sponsored idiom.Copiously illustrated and drawing on previously unpublished documents, Ottoman Baroque breaks new ground in our understanding of Islamic visual culture in the modern era and offers a persuasive counterpoint to Eurocentric accounts of global art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArchitecture, BaroquexInfluence. 0aArchitecture, BaroquezTurkeyzIstanbulxHistoryy18th century. 0aArchitecture, OttomanzTurkeyzIstanbulxHistoryy18th century. 7aART / History / Baroque & Rococo.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190549zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691190549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/c